docs.text: Reference documentation: miBase.py ¶ MiRBase ¶ Main operational class. This class defines which version of database will be used. Defines all available functions to retrieve data by user. __init__ ( self , version = 'CURRENT' ) special ¶ Initializes MiRBase object from which data can be accessed using provided functions. Database version might be specified. There are multiple versions of miRBase database compatible with Mir-Us. Details Parameters: Name Type Description Default version str ID of database version. "CURRENT" is the most recent version (22.1). 'CURRENT' dump_sequences ( self , mirna_obj = None , prec_obj = None , filepath = '' , verbose = False ) ¶ Function writes sequences from given MiRNA or Precursor objects to a file in a FASTA format. Parameters: Name Type Description Default mirna_obj list[MiRNA] List of MiRNA objects, that can be retrieved using get_mirna() function None prec_obj list[Precursor] List of Precursor objects, that can be retrieved using get_precursor() function None filepath str String with the name of the file to which sequences will be saved. '' verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False find_cluster ( self , mirna_id = None , prec_id = None , search_type = 'up-downstream' , range = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns all miRNAs present within given range from given miRNA in affiliated organism genome. Parameters: Name Type Description Default mirna_id str miRNA ID None prec_id str Precursor ID None search_type Union[str, int] Search type which determines how to search genomic space ( additional information ). 'up-downstream' range str Length of genome to be searched None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[list[MiRNA]] miRNA objects matching given criteria or None if no results are found Additional information: ¶ Cluster search types Search type Explanation up-downstream or 0 The search is conducted below and above given miRNA position (towards both ends) within given range. The search is inclusive on both ends of the specified range. upstream or 1 The search is conducted only below given miRNA position (towards 5' end) within given range. The search is inclusive on both ends of the specified range. downstream or 2 The search is conducted only above given miRNA position (towards 3' end) within given range. The search is inclusive on both ends of the specified range. get_mirna ( self , mirna_id = None , name = '' , organism_name = '' , tax_level = '' , chr = '' , start = '' , end = '' , strand = '' , prec_id = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns miRNA objects according to given search criteria. Parameters: Name Type Description Default mirna_id list[str] miRNA IDs None name str Full miRNA name '' organism_name str Full organism name affiliated with miRNA '' tax_level str Taxonomy level affiliated with miRNA '' chr str Chromosome name in which miRNA is present '' start str Genomic location in which miRNA sequence starts '' end str Genomic location in which miRNA sequence ends '' strand str Strand name in which miRNA is present '' prec_id list[str] Affiliated precursor IDs None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[list[MiRNA], dict] list of miRNA objects matching criteria only if single search is conducted. dict only if multiple searches are conducted. For each search type ( additional information ) a list of miRNA objects that matches criteria is returned. Eventually, None if no results are found. Additional information: ¶ miRNA search types There are a few search 'types', depending on search criteria. That means, if the user choose a set of criteria that will be interpreted as contradicting, a separate search will be conducted for each 'type'. This is important, because multiple searches in single function call will return a dictionary with categorized search results. Search types: Search type Set of criteria mirna_id-search Only mirna_id prec_id-search Only prec_id name-search Only name organism-search Only organism_name tax-search Only tax_level chr-search Only chr strand-search Only strand genomic-search organism , chr organism , chr , start organism , chr , end organism , chr , start , end organism , strand organism , strand , start organism , strand , end organism , strand , start , end organism , chr , strand organism , chr , strand , start organism , chr , strand , end organism , chr , strand , start , end Search type is also a key in returned dictionary which allows to access found data. Possible function returns: Condition Returned structure Single search (only one type of search) list of found objects or None Multiple searches (contradicting types) dict of 'type: [found objects]' or None . If certain type of search was unsuccessful, its value will be None get_organism ( self , tax = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns organisms which are assigned to a given taxonomy level. Parameters: Name Type Description Default tax str Full name of taxonomy level None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[list[str]] Full names of organisms representing given taxonomy level or None if no results are found. get_organisms_list ( self ) ¶ Returns list of all organisms. Returns: Type Description list[namedtuple] Organism namedtuple which is organized as follows: Organism(organism='', division='', name='', tree='', taxid='') Organism namedtuple structure explanation Key Explanation organism Organism name abbreviation. division Organism name abbreviation. name Full organism name in latin. tree Full taxonomy path of the organism delimited by ; taxid NCBI taxonomy ID of the organism get_organisms_short ( self , organism = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns dictionary of all organisms names and their abbreviations or a single organism abbreviation. Parameters: Name Type Description Default organism str Full organism name None Returns: Type Description Optional[str, dict] str which is an abbreviation of the given organism name or dict of all abbreviations and its full organism names with the following dictionary structure: (key: abbreviation, value: full organism name) get_precursor ( self , prec_id = None , name = '' , organism_name = '' , tax_level = '' , chr = '' , start = '' , end = '' , strand = '' , mirna_id = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns precursor objects according to a given search criteria Parameters: Name Type Description Default prec_id list[str] Precursor IDs None name str Full precursor name '' organism_name str Full organism name in which precursor is present '' tax_level str Taxonomy level affiliated with precursor '' chr str Chromosome name in which precursor is present '' start str Genomic location in which precursor sequence starts '' end str Genomic location in which precursor sequence ends '' strand str Strand name in which precursor is present '' mirna_id list[str] Affiliated precursor miRNA IDs None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[list[Precursor], dict] list of Precursor objects matching given criteria only if single search is conducted. dict only if multiple searches are conducted. For each search type ( additional information ) a list of Precursor objects that matches criteria is returned. Eventually, None if no results are found. Additional information: ¶ Precursor search types There are a few search 'types', depending on search criteria. That means, if the user choose a set of criteria that will be interpreted as contradicting, a separate search will be conducted for each 'type'. This is important, because multiple searches in single function call will return a dictionary with categorized search results. Search types: Search type Set of criteria mirna_id-search Only mirna_id prec_id-search Only prec_id name-search Only name organism-search Only organism_name tax-search Only tax_level chr-search Only chr strand-search Only strand genomic-search organism , chr organism , chr , start organism , chr , end organism , chr , start , end organism , strand organism , strand , start organism , strand , end organism , strand , start , end organism , chr , strand organism , chr , strand , start organism , chr , strand , end organism , chr , strand , start , end Search type is also a key in returned dictionary which allows to access found data. Possible function returns: Condition Returned structure Single search (only one type of search) list of found objects or None Multiple searches (contradicting types) dict of 'type: [found objects]' or None . If certain type of search was unsuccessful, its value will be None get_references ( self , mirna_id = None , mirna_name = None , prec_id = None , prec_name = None , link = False , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns list of references Parameters: Name Type Description Default mirna_id list[str] IDs of miRNA None mirna_name list[str] Full miRNA names None prec_id list[str] IDs of precursors None prec_name list[str] Full precursor names None link bool A flag, which forces function to return PubMed links instead of reference numbers False verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[dict] Dictionary of precursors or miRNAs ids or names with assigned lists of reference accession numbers or Pubmed links (depending on link flag) (key: precursor or miRNA name or id, value: list of accession numbers or links) or None if no results are found. get_structure ( self , id = None , name = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns dictionary of precursors IDs with assigned structures in dot-bracket format Parameters: Name Type Description Default id list[str] Precursor IDs None name list[str] Full precursor names None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[dict] Dictionary of precursors ids or names with assigned structure (key: precursor name or id, value: structure) or None if no results are found. get_tax_level ( self , organism = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns taxonomy level assigned to organism. Parameters: Name Type Description Default organism list[str] list of organisms names None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[dict] Dictionary of organisms and its assigned taxonomy, which is a list of tax levels (key: organism, value: taxonomy) or None if no results are found. get_taxid ( self , organism = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns NCBI taxonomy ID (taxid) assigned to organism Parameters: Name Type Description Default organism list[str] Full organism name None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[dict] Dictionary of organisms with assigned taxid (key: full organism name, value: taxid) or None if no results are found. get_tree ( self , tax_path = None , verbose = False ) ¶ Returns taxonomy tree, where each taxonomy level is a dictionary (nested dictionaries as access to another taxonomy level and list of organisms at particular taxonomy level if has any) Parameters: Name Type Description Default tax_path list[str] Taxonomy path which indicates tree accession (tree is sliced from positon this path points to) None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[dict] Dictionary structured as taxonomy tree of organisms present in the base (equivalent to Browse miRBase by species ) or its fragment. Returns None if wrong taxonomy path is given. high_conf ( self , mirna_obj = None , prec_obj = None , verbose = False ) ¶ From the given MiRNA or Precursor objects returns only those that are of a high confidence. Parameters: Name Type Description Default mirna_obj list[MiRNA] List of MiRNA objects, that can be retrieved using get_mirna() function None prec_obj list[Precursor] List of Precursor objects, that can be retrieved using get_precursor() function None verbose bool A flag, which allows or disallows showing search details (number of returned elements, time of execution, errors) False Returns: Type Description Optional[list] Filtered MiRNA or Precursor objects that are of a high confidence. Returns None if wrong objects are given or if none of the given objects are of a high confidence.

docs.text: Getting started ¶ This section shows an example usage of the Mir-Us package for the absolute beginner. There are a few steps that have to be done to receive data from miRBase . Import package ¶ To use the package, it must be first imported: from mirus import miBase Initialize miBase object ¶ In order to call functions, a miBase object must be initialized: Example of basic initialization m = miBase . MiRBase () This code above will create a miBase object which will provide functions to retrieve data from the current version of miRBase. However, one might be working on an old project, which requires access to older versions of miRBase. It is possible with Mir-Us. Info Mir-Us supports older versions of miRBase. To use them, the version parameter must be provided. Backwards compatibility does not end on version 20, however. Details Example of initialization with version defining m = miBase . MiRBase ( version = "20" ) # for object 'm' the data from version 20 will be used. The older database is, the fewer data is provided. In extreme cases, even the incomplete data might be returned. Receive data ¶ Receiving data requires the usage of provided functions, each of them is designed for a specific task. For example, one might want to obtain information about existing miRNAs on a human's chromosome X upstream from 153300000 th nucleotide. For this task, the function get_mirna is the most suitable. Example of miRNA search on human's chromosome X from specific genomic location Code data = m . get_mirna ( chr = "chrX" , organism_name = "Homo sapiens" , start = "153300000" , verbose = True ) Result [Mir-Us] 'get_mirna' found 9 results in 0.091857 seconds A list of miRNA objects was returned to the data object, which contain all the parsed information. In the 'Result' tab a search report is printed to the stdout. Search details can be ommited, by setting verbose flag to False or by not including it in the function call. Next steps ¶ With this basic knowledge it is now possible to learn Mir-Us in-depth. If one is looking for specific application of this tool, then it is suggested to read the 'User cookbook'. If one is looking for more specific information about some functionality, then it is advisable to read the 'Reference documentation'. It's time to choose! User cookbook Reference documentation
docs.title: Getting started

If one is looking for more specific information about some functionality, then it is advisable to read the 'Reference documentation'. It's time to choose! User cookbook Reference documentation

docs.title: Change list

docs.text: Compatibility ¶ While designing Mir-Us, we knew that it can't be constrained to the newest version only. We are aware, that many researchers are still using data from a few years ago. That way, we are reaching these people with backwards compatibility that spans as long as 10 years back! But it must be kept in mind, that such vast compatibility is not possible without some trade-offs. Supported versions and their features 22.1 ('CURRENT') Overview : The newest version (December 2018) The amount of entries is identical with version 22: 38589 entries representing miRNA precursor 48885 entries representing mature miRNA 271 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - Recalculated high confidence miRNA set: 2162 (version 22) 3320 (version 22.1) No known issues 22 Overview : Version released in March 2018 38589 entries representing miRNA precursor 48885 entries representing mature miRNA 271 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - 10031 new precursor sequences - 13149 new mature products - 48 new species - 115 precursors and 496 mature miRNAs have changed names - 87 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted - Recalculated high confidence miRNA set: 1996 (version 21) 2162 (version 22) No known issues Detailed change list 21 Overview : Version released in June 2014 28645 entries representing miRNA precursor 35828 entries representing mature miRNA 223 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - 4196 new precursor sequences - 5441 new mature products - 17 new species - High confidence miRNA set was created (1996 entries labeled as of high confidence) - 169 precursors and 353 mature miRNAs have changed names - 72 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted Issue Some of .gff files are different comparing to version 22 or above. There are possible inconsistencies and differences in chromosome names. Detailed change list 20 Overview : Version released in June 2013 24521 entries representing miRNA precursor 30424 entries representing mature miRNA 206 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - 3355 new precursor sequences - 5393 new mature products - 13 new species - 144 precursors and 810 mature miRNAs have changed names - 98 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted Issue Some of .gff files are different comparing to version 22 or above. There are possible inconsistencies and differences in chromosome names. Missing feature This version does not define high confidence set of miRNA, thus high_confidence fields will be set to default value which is False . Detailed change list 19 Overview : Version released in August 2012 21264 entries representing miRNA precursor 25141 entries representing mature miRNA 193 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - 3171 new precursor sequences - 3625 new mature products - 25 new species - 313 precursors and 4666 mature miRNAs have changed names - Mature sequences from all species are now designated -5p and -3p, rather than miR/miR*. - over 130 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted Issue Some of .gff files are different comparing to version 22 or above. There are possible inconsistencies and differences in chromosome names. Issue Since version 19, the files with organisms data are lacking NCBI taxonomy ID. Without this information function get_taxid would be rendered obsolete and data structure redesign should be conducted. To keep the intended functionality and structural consistency alongside further compatibility, current taxonomy IDs are retrieved from NCBI database based on organism names availible in data files from version 19. This largely solves the problem, but some organism names were changed and as a result some records might be lacking in organism/taxonomy data. Missing feature This version does not define high confidence set of miRNA, thus high_confidence fields will be set to default value which is False . Detailed change list 18 Overview : Version released in November 2011 18226 entries representing miRNA precursor 21643 entries representing mature miRNA 168 species in which all entries are found Differences from previous version : - 1488 new precursor sequences - 1929 new mature products - 50 precursors and 1417 mature miRNAs have changed names - Mature sequences from all human, mouse, and C. elegans precursors are now designated -5p and -3p, rather than miR/miR*. - over 45 misannotated and duplicate sequences have been deleted Issue Some of .gff files are different comparing to version 22 or above. There are possible inconsistencies and differences in chromosome names. Issue Since version 19, the files with organisms data are lacking NCBI taxonomy ID. Without this information function get_taxid would be rendered obsolete and data structure redesign should be conducted. To keep the intended functionality and structural consistency alongside further compatibility, current taxonomy IDs are retrieved from NCBI database based on organism names availible in data files from version 19. This largely solves the problem, but some organism names were changed and as a result some records might be lacking in organism/taxonomy data. Issue Mir-Us sometimes relies on names and different naming convention is suspected to render some records lacking names or will cause assignment of the incorrrect name from the perspective of newer versions (e.g. certain names can be incorrectly trimmed) to which Mir-Us is native. Missing feature This version does not define high confidence set of miRNA, thus high_confidence fields will be set to the default value which is False . Detailed change list
